05613nam a22010215i 9780691214832DE-B159720210202111235.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210202t20202002nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912148327 a10.1515/97806912148322doi  a(DE-B1597)563247  a(OCoLC)1191863977  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aLIT0040202bisacsh04a813/.5092221 aMcGurl, Mark, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Novel Art :bElevations of American Fiction after Henry James /cMark McGurl. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2002  a1 online resource (232 p.) :b2 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. The Rise of the Art-Novel and the Question of Glass -- tOne. The Mind's Eye and Mental Labor: Forms of Distinction in the Fiction of Henry James -- tTwo. Social Geometries: Taking Place in the Jamesian Modernist Text -- tThree. Downward Mobilities: The Prison of the Womb and the Architecture of Career in Stephen Crane -- tFour. Highbrows and Dumb Blondes: Literary Intellectuals and the Romance of Intelligence -- tFive. Faulkner s Ambit: Modernism, Regionalism, and the Location of Cultural Capital -- tSix. Making "Literature" of It: Dashiell Hammett and the Mysteries of High Culture -- tAfterword. Mobius Fictions -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOnce upon a time there were good American novels and bad ones, but none was thought of as a work of art. The Novel Art tells the story of how, beginning with Henry James, this began to change. Examining the late-nineteenth century movement to elevate the status of the novel, its sources, paradoxes, and reverberations into the twentieth century, Mark McGurl presents a more coherent and wide-ranging account of the development of American modernist fiction than ever before. Moving deftly from James to Stephen Crane, Edith Wharton, Gertrude Stein, William Faulkner, Dashiell Hammett, and Djuna Barnes among others, McGurl argues that what unifies this diverse group of ambitious writers is their agonized relation to a middling genre rarely included in discussions of the fine arts. He concludes that the new product, despite its authors' desire to distinguish it from popular forms, never quite forsook the intimacy the genre had long cultivated with the common reader. Indeed, the ''art novel'' sought status within the mass market, and among its prime strategies was a promotion of the mind as a source of value in an economy increasingly dependent on mental labor. McGurl also shows how modernism's obsessive interest in simple-mindedness revealed a continued concern with the masses even as it attempted to use this simplicity to produce a heightened sophistication of form. Masterfully argued and set in elegant prose, The Novel Art provides a rich new understanding of the fascinating road the American novel has taken from being an artless enterprise to an aesthetic one.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Feb 2021) 0aAmerican fictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aFictionxTechnique. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh  aBlack Mask.  aBush, Ronald.  aConrad, Joseph.  aDebray, Regis.  aFried, Michael.  aFugitive-Agrarians.  aGather, Willa.  aGrimwood, Michael.  aHemingway, Ernest.  aJameson, Fredric.  aJoyce, James.  aKnopf.  aKreyliug, Michael.  aLevine, Lawrence.  aLiveright, Horace.  aMalraux, Andre.  aMcKeon, Michael.  aMencken.  aOliphant, Margaret.  aStein, Gertrud.  aanthropology.  aavant-garde.  adetective novel.  aeducation.  agender.  ahigh art.  aimagetext.  aimmigration.  anativism.  anaturalism.  ap